–1331","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1293–1356":"1293–1356","1220–Male":"1220–Overleden","1222–Female":"1222–Overleden","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1356":"1356","1222":"1222","1255":"1255","1331":"1331","about 1255":"circa 1255","1306":"1306","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sampford Peverell, Devon, England":"Sampford Peverell, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1255–1331":"about 1255–1331","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1293–1356":"1293–1356","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1222–Female":"1222–Deceased","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1356":"1356","1222":"1222","1255":"1255","1331":"1331","about 1255":"about 1255","1306":"1306","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sampford Peverell, Devon, England":"Sampford Peverell, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Halton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from any of several places called Halton in Cheshire, Lancashire, Yorkshire, Northumberland, Lincolnshire, Shropshire and Buckinghamshire. Halton is usually from Old English <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. Halton in Cheshire, however, is possibly named from an Old English <i>hāthel</i> ‘heathery place’ + <i>tūn</i>, and Halton in Northumberland from an Old English <i>hāw</i> ‘look out’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish: variant of   Holton  .","History: Most English bearers of this name trace their descent from William de Halton, who was living at Halton, Lancashire, in 1346."],"variants":[{"name":"Holton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Holton, such as those in Oxfordshire, Suffolk, Dorset, and Somerset. The Oxfordshire and Somerset placenames derive from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Suffolk placename comes from the Old English personal name <i>Hōla</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Dorset placename derives from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ or <i>holt</i> ‘wood, grove, thicket’ + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish: altered form of <b>O'Haltahan</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUltacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ultachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Ultach</i> ‘Ulsterman’. This is a rare Fermanagh surname, sometimes Anglicized as   Nolan  ."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":60,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":73,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna de Halton was born about 1255, in Devon, England, her father, John de Halton, was 37 and her mother, Margaret Bloyou, was 35. She had at least 1 son with Roger de Inkepenne. She died in 1331, at the age of 77."},"et":{"about 1255–1331":"umbes 1255–1331","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1293–1356":"1293–1356","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1222–Female":"1222–Surnud","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1356":"1356","1222":"1222","1255":"1255","1331":"1331","about 1255":"umbes 1255","1306":"1306","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sampford Peverell, Devon, England":"Sampford Peverell, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1255–1331":"noin 1255–1331","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1293–1356":"1293–1356","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1222–Female":"1222–Kuollut","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1356":"1356","1222":"1222","1255":"1255","1331":"1331","about 1255":"noin 1255","1306":"1306","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sampford Peverell, Devon, England":"Sampford Peverell, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1255–1331":"environ 1255–1331","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1250–1306":"1250–1306","1293–1356":"1293–1356","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","1222–Female":"1222–Décédée","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1356":"1356","1222":"1222","1255":"1255","1331":"1331","about 1255":"environ 1255","1306":"1306","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sampford Peverell, Devon, England":"Sampford Peverell, Devon, Angleterre","Devon, England":"De